article.description:
Elton Brand, Quentin Richardson and Andre Miller
led a fourth-quarter rally that propelled the Los Angeles Clippers
over the Phoenix Suns 107-106 Tuesday night.
article.headline: Clippers end six-game road losing streak
article.linkText: Road-weary Clippers rally to stun Suns in Phoenix
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- With the worst record in the Pacific Division, the Los Angeles Clippers have little other than pride to play for this season.
Brand

That wasn't apparent against the Phoenix Suns on Tuesday night. Elton Brand, Quentin Richardson and Andre Miller led a fourth-quarter rally that propelled the Clippers over the Suns 107-106. "It's too late for us now, but we're not going to give up,'' Brand said. "We want to take something good into next season. We can be the spoilers now.'' The Clippers, who had lost six straight road games and were only 7-17 away from home, trailed by five points starting the final period. But with Miller scoring 10 points, Richardson seven and Brand six, they outscored the Suns 30-24 for their first road win since Jan. 22 at Utah. After trailing 94-88 with 7:22 remaining, the Clippers went on a 15-2 burst to go ahead 103-96, their largest lead of the game. Los Angeles also controlled the Suns in the paint, outscoring them 62-34. "We beat the team that's been the best down the stretch,'' Brand said. "After a lackluster first half of the season, we wanted to establish ourselves, and we did that tonight. "We put together 48 minutes. Usually, we play only part of the game.'' The Suns had won three straight before the All-Star game, 13 of their previous 14 home games and had the best home record in the Pacific Division (20-4) before the loss. Brand led the Clippers with 29 points and 11 rebounds, Richardson had 20, Miller 19 and Lamar Odom 16. "A lot of people didn't think we had anything to play for, but we did,'' Odom said. "If we play well down the stretch, they might think about keeping this team together next season.'' There has been much talk that the Clippers will be broken up prior to next season. Brand, Odom, Corey Maggette, Miller and Michael Olowokandi all were eligible for contract extensions last summer, but none got them. "The big thing that fueled our 15-2 run was defensive stops,'' Los Angeles coach Alvin Gentry said. Stephon Marbury scored 33 points for the Suns, including a 3-pointer as time expired. Shawn Marion had 22 points, Joe Johnson 21 and Amare Stoudemire added 12 points and 13 rebounds. "We scored 106, certainly good enough to win,'' Phoenix coach Frank Johnson said, "but when you can't stop anyone, when we allow them to shoot 53 percent from the field, you aren't going to beat many teams in this league.'' This was the final meeting of the season between the teams, and the Clippers' victory prevented the Suns from finishing with a 4-0 sweep. Los Angeles trailed for most of the first half, but left the court at halftime with a 59-58 lead on Miller's reverse layup with 9.3 seconds remaining. Los Angeles got a lot of help from its bench, with Richardson scoring 13 points, including 3-of-4 3-pointers, and little-used Melvin Ely adding nine, all in the second quarter. Overall in the half, the Clippers' reserves outscored the Suns' bench 26-2. They finished with a 33-8 edge. The Clippers never led until Richardson drained a 3-pointer with 1:45 remaining in the second quarter for a 51-49 advantage. The Suns' biggest lead was 10 points, 44-34, with 8:46 to go in the half on a 3-pointer by Marion. The Suns came out running in the third period. After Brand opened with a breakaway dunk, Phoenix went on a 14-2 run to lead 72-63. Twice they increased the lead to 11, but the Clippers came charging right back and scored the final six points of the quarter to trail only 82-77 going into the final 12 minutes. Game notes
The Suns are in the midst of a six-game, 19-day homestand which began Feb. 1. They still have home games remaining against New York, Boston and Houston before embarking on a four-game road trip against Toronto on Feb. 21. ... Of the Suns' three injured starters from the start of the season -- Tom Gugliotta, Penny Hardaway and Jake Tsakilidis -- Gugliotta is expected to be the first to return, for the start of the road trip. Gugliotta is recovering from a stress fracture in his right foot, Hardaway from an injured thumb -- he had the pin removed Tuesday -- and Tsakilidis from back surgery. Hardaway and Tsakilidis are not expected to return until March. ... The Clippers have had 13 players lose 168 games to injuries this season, sixth-highest in the NBA. Toronto leads the league with 323 games lost, followed by Sacramento with 221.
